### do-while Loop in C#

The `do-while` loop is similar to `while`, but it guarantees that the code block executes at least once before checking the condition.

### Syntax

```csharp
do
{
    // Code to execute at least once
} while (condition);
```

### Basic Example

```csharp
int i = 0;
do
{
    Console.WriteLine($"Count: {i}");
    i++;
} while (i < 5);
```

### while vs do-while

| Aspect | while | do-while |
|--------|-------|----------|
| Condition check | Before execution | After execution |
| Minimum executions | 0 | 1 |
| Semantics | Entry-controlled | Exit-controlled |

### When condition is initially false

```csharp
int x = 100;

while (x < 10)  // Never executes
{
    Console.WriteLine("while: " + x);
}

do               // Executes once
{
    Console.WriteLine("do-while: " + x);
} while (x < 10);
```

### Menu-Driven Program Pattern

```csharp
string choice;
do
{
    Console.WriteLine("\n=== MENU ===");
    Console.WriteLine("1. Add");
    Console.WriteLine("2. Delete");
    Console.WriteLine("3. Exit");
    Console.Write("Choice: ");

    choice = Console.ReadLine();

    switch (choice)
    {
        case "1": Console.WriteLine("Adding..."); break;
        case "2": Console.WriteLine("Deleting..."); break;
        case "3": Console.WriteLine("Goodbye!"); break;
        default: Console.WriteLine("Invalid choice"); break;
    }
} while (choice != "3");
```

### Input Validation

```csharp
string input;
do
{
    Console.Write("Enter 'yes' or 'no': ");
    input = Console.ReadLine().ToLower();
} while (input != "yes" && input != "no");

Console.WriteLine($"You entered: {input}");
```

> **Key Point:** Use do-while when you need the code to run at least once before checking the condition. Common use cases include menu systems and input validation where you need to show options or prompt user before checking exit conditions.

### do-while Scope

```csharp
do
{
    int temp = 5;  // Local to block
    Console.WriteLine(temp);
} while (false);
// Console.WriteLine(temp);  // Error - temp is out of scope
```

codeExample:
using System;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        int number;
        do
        {
            Console.Write("Enter a positive number: ");
        } while (!int.TryParse(Console.ReadLine(), out number) || number <= 0);

        Console.WriteLine($"You entered: {number}");

        // Countdown from number
        do
        {
            Console.Write($"{number} ");
            number--;
        } while (number > 0);

        Console.WriteLine("\nDone!");
    }
}
